pr_review_body:
I'm OK with this as a quick fix, but it would be better to understand the root cause of the issue. AFAIK Python inheritance should take care of this problem, and it does seem to work when tested manually.

```
class A:
   def inner(self):
       print("A")

   def outer(self):
       self.inner()

class B(A):
   def inner(self):
       print("B")

class C(B):
   def inner(self):
       print("C")


a = A()
a.outer() # -> A
b = B()
b.outer() # -> B
c = C()
c.outer() # -> C
```

@brianljt thank you for this.

Shouldn't we reference to power on the antenna connector for each functionality, and so add/decrement the offset (LNA Gain) in the following functions:

`nrf_802154_energy_detected`, `nrf_802154_received_timestamp_raw`, `nrf_802154_transmitted_raw`, `otPlatRadioGetRssi`?

For example:
```
void nrf_802154_energy_detected(uint8_t result)
{
    sEnergyDetected = nrf_802154_dbm_from_energy_level_calculate(result) - sLnaGain;

    setPendingEvent(kPendingEventEnergyDetected);
}
```

I left some initial comments; 

High level comment is; 

- The manager class APIs seem a bit brittle (especially with cache). Can we use ABCClass to have abstract methods? I also think we should hide cache behind the manager's create/delete APIs. It seems doable in the first glance, but lmk if you think it can't be
- Cache means the agent becomes stateful, which means the behavior after agent restarts is undefined. Is there a design for how to handle this? Also, if we don't handle this right now, can we make this feature off by default? We shouldn't have non-fully working feature just for the sake of performance optimization, especially when the feature is already GA (this also seems to be regression without fault handling?)

@sallysyw 
> I converted the classy-vision's vitc checkpoints into torchvision's checkpoints and made sure that for a random input, the torchvision model and classyvision model produce the same output.

This is great, thanks for checking. There is a significant amount of code that is not covered by any test. Since this is a feature of substantial size, we will need to cover it. Because we don't have a dedicated model builder method that uses the feature, it won't be tested by our standard `test_classification_model`. A quick workaround is to add a new test in [test_models.py](https://github.com/pytorch/vision/blob/main/test/test_models.py), define a nested simplified model builder within it and pass it as param to the `test_classification_model` method. The rest remains the same from there (you will need an expected file etc).

